abstract.t:
This document specifies the extensions to the Access Node Control Protocol (ANCP) (RFC 6320) required for support of the multicast use cases defined in the Access Node Control Protocol framework document (RFC 5851) and one additional use case described in this document. These use cases are organized into the following ANCP capabilities:
multicast replication initiated by the Network Access Server (NAS);
conditional access and admission control with white and black lists;
conditional access and admission control with grey lists;
bandwidth delegation; and
committed bandwidth reporting.
These capabilities may be combined according to the rules given in this specification.

section.t:
supports, specifically for DSL access, three use cases defined in : the Topology Discovery use case, the Line Configuration use case, and the Remote Connectivity Test use case. However, it does not support the multicast use cases defined in . The present document specifies the extensions to the Access Node Control Protocol required for support of these multicast use cases. In addition, it supports the Committed Bandwidth Reporting use case, described below. In terms of ANCP, these use cases are organized into five capabilities:
NAS-initiated multicast replication;
conditional access and admission control with white and black lists;
conditional access and admission control with grey lists;
bandwidth delegation; and
committed bandwidth reporting.

The Message Type for the Bandwidth Transfer message is 147. The Bandwidth Transfer message contains the following TLVs:
the Target TLV, designating the access line concerned;
an instance of the Bandwidth-Allocation TLV (). The bandwidth value in the Bandwidth-Allocation TLV is the new amount of delegated bandwidth allocated to the target.

Section 3.5 of defines a capability negotiation mechanism as well as a number of capabilities. This section defines five new capabilities in support of different modes of multicast operation:
NAS-initiated multicast replication (capability type 3);
committed bandwidth reporting (capability type 5);
conditional access and admission control with white and black lists (capability type 6);
conditional access and admission control with grey lists (capability type 7); and
bandwidth delegation (capability type 8).
